Hello,
I have a simple exe that embeds the python interpreter, exposes a local variable and runs a script. The code is the following:
```c++
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {

    py::scoped_interpreter guard{};
    auto locals = py::dict("name"_a="my_name");
    // create a local reference
    py::exec(R"(
s = locals()["name"]
print s
    )", py::globals(), locals);    
    // evaluate a script 
    if (argc > 1) {
        py::eval_file(argv[1], py::globals(), locals);
    }

    return 0;
}
```

if I run the following script:
```py
global_dict = { "key1" : "new_name1", "key2" : "new_name2" }

print("value of s: {}".format(s))
s = global_dict["key1"]
print("value of s: {}".format(s))
```
everything runs as expected, but it doesn't work if instead I run the following script, that is functionally equivalent but access the `global_dict` from a function:
```py
global_dict = { "key1" : 11, "key2" : 12 }

def my_func(s):
    s = global_dict["key1"]

print("value of s: {}".format(s))
my_func(s)
print("value of s: {}".format(s))
```
the euro that I get is the following:
```
libc++abi.dylib: terminating with uncaught exception of type pybind11::error_already_set: NameError: global name 'global_dict' is not defined

At:
  script1.py(5): my_func
  script1.py(8): <module>

[1]    33087 abort      ./test script1.py
```

If I call `py::eval_file` without the `locals` parameter (and of course without using the local var defined in the c++ code) I don't see the same problem, and functions can access global variables.

Am I missing something when making the call?

Attached an archive that reproduces the problem with the latest master of pybind11 (431fc0e):
[pybind11_testcase_globalname.zip](https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/files/1755763/pybind11_testcase_globalname.zip)
If you build and run with `./test script1.py` you'll see the problem (only tested on MacOS, using system python 2.7).

Thanks for your support and for this library!
